England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Elton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Elton (Berkshire, Cheshire, Derbyshire, Durham, Herefordshire, Huntingdonshire, Lancashire, and Nottinghamshire). The Eltons in Chesire, Derbyshire, and Durham are from Old English <i>ǣl</i> ‘eel’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. Elton in Berkshire is from the Old English female personal name <i>Æthelflǣd</i> (composed of the elements <i>æthel</i> ‘noble’ + <i>flǣd</i> ‘beauty’). Both Elton in Herefordshire and in Nottinghamshire are from the Old English personal name <i>Ella</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Berkshire origin for the surname is especially well represented.","Norwegian: habitational name from a farm name in eastern Norway, in Old Norse <i>Elgjartún</i> ‘enclosed sacred place’ (or fenced in for <i>elg</i> ‘moose’?)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Bridget","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Gaelic Brighid (pronounced ‘breed’); . This was the name of an ancient Celtic goddess, which in Gaulish would have been <i>Brigindos</i>, meaning ‘the exalted one’.  St Brigid  of Kildare (  <i>c.</i>450– <i>c.</i>525 ) is one of the patron saints of Ireland. Very few facts are known about her life. She founded a religious house for women at Kildare, and is said to be have been buried at Downpatrick, where  St Patrick  and  St Columba  were also buried. Many of the stories of miracles told about  St Brigid  seem to be Christianized versions of pagan legends concerning the goddess. The popularity of the name was further reinforced throughout Europe, especially in Scandinavia in the form  <b>Birgit</b> , as the name of the patron saint of Sweden (  1304–73 ). She was a noblewoman of Irish stock who, after the death of her husband, founded an order of nuns, the Bridgettines. Later she went to Rome and attempted to introduce religious reforms there."],"variants":[{"name":"Bridgid","meanings":["Anglicized form of Gaelic Brighid (pronounced ‘breed’); . This was the name of an ancient Celtic goddess, which in Gaulish would have been <i>Brigindos</i>, meaning ‘the exalted one’.  St Brigid  of Kildare (  <i>c.</i>450– <i>c.</i>525 ) is one of the patron saints of Ireland. Very few facts are known about her life. She founded a religious house for women at Kildare, and is said to be have been buried at Downpatrick, where  St Patrick  and  St Columba  were also buried. Many of the stories of miracles told about  St Brigid  seem to be Christianized versions of pagan legends concerning the goddess. The popularity of the name was further reinforced throughout Europe, especially in Scandinavia in the form  <b>Birgit</b> , as the name of the patron saint of Sweden (  1304–73 ). She was a noblewoman of Irish stock who, after the death of her husband, founded an order of nuns, the Bridgettines. Later she went to Rome and attempted to introduce religious reforms there."]},{"name":"Bridgit","meanings":["Anglicized form of Gaelic Brighid (pronounced ‘breed’); . This was the name of an ancient Celtic goddess, which in Gaulish would have been <i>Brigindos</i>, meaning ‘the exalted one’.  St Brigid  of Kildare (  <i>c.</i>450– <i>c.</i>525 ) is one of the patron saints of Ireland. Very few facts are known about her life. She founded a religious house for women at Kildare, and is said to be have been buried at Downpatrick, where  St Patrick  and  St Columba  were also buried. Many of the stories of miracles told about  St Brigid  seem to be Christianized versions of pagan legends concerning the goddess. The popularity of the name was further reinforced throughout Europe, especially in Scandinavia in the form  <b>Birgit</b> , as the name of the patron saint of Sweden (  1304–73 ). She was a noblewoman of Irish stock who, after the death of her husband, founded an order of nuns, the Bridgettines. Later she went to Rome and attempted to introduce religious reforms there."]},{"name":"Brigid","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘the exalted one’.  See  <b>Bridget</b>   ."]},{"name":"Brigit","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘the exalted one’.  See  <b>Bridget</b>   ."]},{"name":"Brighid","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘the exalted one’.  See  <b>Bridget</b>   ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":6,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":41,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Bridget Elton was born in 1218, in Pickering, Yorkshire, England, her father, Sir Hugh Elton, was 20 and her mother, Bridgett, was 19. She married Sir Bryan de Woodrove in 1180, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1277, in England, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1218–1277":"1218–1277","1215–1260":"1215–1260","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1222–Male":"1222–Surnud","1236–Male":"1236–Surnud","1232–Male":"1232–Surnud","1240–1313":"1240–1313","1198–1246":"1198–1246","1199–Female":"1199–Surnud","1198":"1198","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1313":"1313","1246":"1246","1224":"1224","1222":"1222","1277":"1277","1232":"1232","1199":"1199","1155":"1155","before 1260":"enne 1260","1218":"1218","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Pickering, Yorkshire, England":"Pickering, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Woolley, Yor